#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: v2-user-type-shadows-plugin-type
description: a user case class sharing a name with a plugin-owned runtime type (e.g. Request) has its fields shadowed by the plugin's field list on v2
backends: [int]
---

# v2 fresh regression: user `case class Request` collides with the plugin-owned `Request` type

Regression from `d5f9ce486` (fix(v2): batch-isolate the fieldNames
registry via snapshot/restore — the fix for `v2-route-params-stub`).

`V2PluginRegistry.fieldNames` is a single GLOBAL, tag-keyed map. Plugin
load registers a baseline entry for the runtime-owned `Request` tag (used
by `std/http.ssc`'s `Request`, so `req.params`/`req.query`/etc resolve —
see `v2-route-params-stub`, now fixed). `snapshot()` now captures that
baseline and `restore()` resets `fieldNames` to it — but restore is (or a
prior overwrite is) NOT scoped per-tag against USER case classes: any
program that ALSO declares its OWN `case class Request(...)` (a completely
unrelated type — this repro's has no `method`/`path`/`headers` at all)
gets its field registration for tag "Request" clobbered by the plugin's
http-Request field list. Field access then resolves by the WRONG
(http-shaped) index/registry, `id` isn't in it, and the value comes back
as `Stub` — silently, with no compile or import connection to
`std/http.ssc` at all (this repro imports NOTHING).

busi hit this via `src/v2/domain/requests.ssc`'s OWN
`case class Request(id, partyId, kind, ...)` (an inbox-request domain
type, unrelated to HTTP) — `.id` on it now returns `Stub` on `--v2`,
regressing `tests/v2/requests.ssc` from passing to
`RuntimeException: head on empty list`. v1 lanes below pin the correct
behavior.

Found 2026-07-09 by busi (fable), same afternoon `v2-route-params-stub`'s
fix landed.

```scalascript
case class Request(id: String, kind: String)

val items = List(Request("r1", "task"), Request("r2", "investor"))
val hit = items.filter(r => r.id == "r1").head
println(hit.id)
println(hit.kind)
```
